Part 1:
1) I would choose a row key like VIN-Model-Make-City. This way queries related to Make or City will be efficient as those attributes are located in the row key and so will be efficient to access. This choice prevents "hotspotting" as the VIN is likely a unique identification number so each tablet will see a random distribution of rows without any one being a hotspot due to none specifically containing every single car for the same Make or City which queries will likely be on.
2) I would have the following column families: 
IDs: VIN (1-10),DOL Vehicle ID
Location: County,City,State,Postal Code,Vehicle Location,Legislative District,2020 Census Tract
MetaData: Model Year,Make,Model,Electric Vehicle Type,Clean Alternative Fuel Vehicle (CAFV) Eligibility,Electric Range,Electric Utility.
This approach groups the columns into 3 column families and thus allows for queries that use related attributes to have optimal performance as column families are split into locality groups that allow for faster access to the specific column qualifiers.
3) If a hash based shard key is used then cluster performance will be optimal as there will be less chance of hotspotting occurring as the values will be randomly distributed based off of the hash function. However, the performance of things like range based queries or queries that access related attributes will diminish as they might be located in different shards which will affect performance. A range based shard key will result in more optimal performance of ranged queries as related values will be stored in close locality to one another, however, this method is very susceptible to hotspotting as certain ranges might be more common for queries to target than others which can reduce cluster performance as some clusters might get a lot of work whereas others aren't used as much.
Part 4:
Average latency for fast insert: 0.0731
Average latency for safe insert: 0.0740
Based off the latency and the CAP theorem I would pick the faster, primary-only write preference for a scenario like inserting log data from a sensor.
